    {
      "title": "Establishing the Sorted Requirement",
      "content": "Binary search only works on **sorted datasets**. Because the data is in order, we can make assumptions about where our target value might be located relative to any chosen point."
    },
    {
      "title": "The Midpoint Strategy",
      "content": "Instead of checking every element (Linear Search), we look at the middle element. \n\n`mid = floor((low + high) / 2)`\n\nIf our target is `70` and the midpoint is `48`, we know for a fact that `70` must be to the right of `48`."
    },
    {
      "title": "Eliminating the Search Space",
      "content": "Since `70 > 48`, we discard the entire left half of the array. This reduces our problem size by 50% in a single step. We repeat this process until the target is found or the range is empty. This results in a time complexity of **O(log n)**."
    }
  ],
